<section xml:id="ref.data.mutable">
<title>Mutable Values</title>

<para><emphasis role="strong">Type</emphasis>: <code>TODO</code></para>

<para>For the purposes of this section, a <firstterm>mutable value</firstterm> is a value that is
not referentially transparent.  That is, use of a mutable value in an expression is not
guaranteed to always be the same as replacing the expression with its result. The expression
could yield different results when the mutable value is used at different times.
(We disregard timing and performance effects in this discussion.)</para>

<para>Mutable values are common in imperative programming languages.  They reflect the
concept of a storage location in a von Neumann-style architecture.  
Most of Orc's value types are immutable.</para>

<para>Orc provides the following standard mutable value types:
<itemizedlist>
<listitem><para><code><xref linkend="library.state.Ref"/></code>: Reference to a value that can be changed</para></listitem>
<listitem><para><code><xref linkend="library.state.Cell"/></code>: A write-once Ref</para></listitem>
<listitem><para><code><xref linkend="library.state.Buffer"/></code>: A queue of values</para></listitem>
<listitem><para><code><xref linkend="library.state.BoundedBuffer"/></code>: A queue of values with a maximum size</para></listitem>
<listitem><para><code><xref linkend="library.state.Array"/></code>: A mutable integer-indexed sequence of values</para></listitem>
<listitem><para><code><xref linkend="library.state.Set"/></code>: A mutable set of values</para></listitem>
<listitem><para><code><xref linkend="library.state.Counter"/></code>: A value that can be incremented and decremented atomically </para></listitem>
<listitem><para><code><xref linkend="library.state.Dictionary"/></code>: A mutable Record</para></listitem>
</itemizedlist>
See the reference manual entries for each of these types for details and examples.
</para>


